                    <h3>üìñ Effective Study Strategies</h3>
                    <p>Master these proven techniques to boost your academic performance:</p>

                    <div style="margin-top: 20px;">
                        <h4>1. The Feynman Technique</h4>
                        <p><strong>How it works:</strong> Choose a topic ‚Üí Explain it in simple terms as if teaching a
                            5-year-old ‚Üí Find gaps in your understanding ‚Üí Simplify and refine.</p>
                        <p><strong>Why it works:</strong> Identifying what you DON'T know is the first step to learning
                            it. This technique surfaces gaps quickly.</p>
                    </div>

                    <div style="margin-top: 20px;">
                        <h4>2. Spaced Repetition</h4>
                        <p><strong>How it works:</strong> Review material at increasing intervals (1 day, 3 days, 7
                            days, 14 days, 30 days).</p>
                        <p><strong>Why it works:</strong> Fighting the "forgetting curve" - reviewing just as you're
                            about to forget maximizes retention.</p>
                        <p style="color: #666; font-size: 0.9rem;">üí° Apps like Anki automate spaced repetition with
                            flashcards.</p>
                    </div>

                    <div style="margin-top: 20px;">
                        <h4>3. Active Learning (Not Passive)</h4>
                        <p><strong>Active: ‚ùå</strong> Highlighting, re-reading, passive note-taking</p>
                        <p><strong>Passive: ‚úÖ</strong> Self-testing, practice problems, teaching others, creating mind
                            maps</p>
                        <p><strong>Why it works:</strong> Your brain retains 90% of what you DO, but only 10% of what
                            you READ.</p>
                    </div>

                    <div style="margin-top: 20px;">
                        <h4>4. Interleaving</h4>
                        <p><strong>How it works:</strong> Mix different topics/problem types during study instead of
                            blocking (all topic A, then all topic B).</p>
                        <p><strong>Why it works:</strong> Your brain learns to discriminate between concepts and chooses
                            the right strategy faster.</p>
                    </div>
                </section>

